In this example, `useEffect` runs when the page is displayed, allowing you to perform tasks like fetching data or logging. The return function acts like cleanup when navigating away from the page.

Here's a complete example using `useEffect` in a `HookWidget` to perform actions when the page is displayed or navigated back to:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_hooks/flutter_hooks.dart';

class MyPage extends HookWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    useEffect(() {
      // Called when the page is shown
      print('Page is shown or navigated back to');

      // Optional cleanup when navigating away
      return () {
        print('Page is disposed or popped');
      };
    }, []);

    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text('My Page')),
      body: Center(
        child: Text('Welcome Back!'),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

In this example, the `print` statement inside the `useEffect` will execute each time the page is shown or navigated back to. The cleanup function runs when the page is popped from the navigation stack.

